<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Known from a few collections from three localities in southwestern Greenland. 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. colvinii" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="colvinii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. colvinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Peck, CH" journalOrPublisher="North American Fungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B39" refString="Peck, CH, 1875. Report of the Botanist (1874) Annual Report on the New York State Museum of Natural History 28: 31-88." title="Report of the Botanist (1874) Annual Report on the New York State Museum of Natural History 28: 31 - 88." year="1875">Peck (1875</bibRefCitation>
; effectively published 1876) from West Albany in North America. He found it in drifting sand in West Albany near Albany, N.Y. State. Later 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.58545" author="Kauffman, CH" journalOrPublisher="Wynkoop Hallenbeck Crawford Co., Lansing" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B29" refString="Kauffman, CH, 1918. The Agaricaceae of Michigan. Wynkoop Hallenbeck Crawford Co., Lansing, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.58545" title="The Agaricaceae of Michigan." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.58545" year="1918">Kauffman (1918)</bibRefCitation>
reported this or a very similar species from New Richmond in Michigan, as did 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00131724609339958" author="Ritchie, D" journalOrPublisher="Castanea" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="125 - 127" refId="B41" refString="Ritchie, D, 1946. Hebeloma colvini, a rare mushroom from a sandy beach. Castanea 11: 125 - 127, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00131724609339958" title="Hebeloma colvini, a rare mushroom from a sandy beach." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00131724609339958" volume="11" year="1946">Ritchie (1946)</bibRefCitation>
from Lewes, Delaware Bay. Neither of these two collections has been examined as part of this study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Five collections, all with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in pure sand along a river. In one of the localities, Sandflugtsdalen (&quot;valley of driftsand&quot;) at Kangerlussuaq, it was very common and scattered over a large area. The sand is mineral-rich due to mixing with loess.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sacc.; Syll. fung. (Abellini) 5: 805" authorityYear="1887" baseAuthorityName="Peck" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma colvinii" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colvinii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma colvinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Agaricaceae" genus="Agaricus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Agaricus</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma colvini" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colvini">Hebeloma colvini</taxonomicName>
&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Peck, CH" journalOrPublisher="North American Fungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B39" refString="Peck, CH, 1875. Report of the Botanist (1874) Annual Report on the New York State Museum of Natural History 28: 31-88." title="Report of the Botanist (1874) Annual Report on the New York State Museum of Natural History 28: 31 - 88." year="1875">Peck 1875</bibRefCitation>
). The name is currently not in use, e.g. there are no records on Mushroom Observer (https://mushroomobserver.org/, accessed 23 Sept 2020) and while Mycoportal (https://mycoportal.org/portal/collections/list.php, accessed 2 Dec 2020) has 63 records, the most recent is from 1972. The identification of the Greenland collections is supported by unpublished studies of type material. It appears that exposed expanses of sandy soil are the characteristic habitat for the species, which is morphologically similar to a number of species of the difficult group around 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. dunense" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="dunense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. dunense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sacc.; Syll. fung. (Abellini) 5: 805" authorityYear="1887" baseAuthorityName="Peck" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma colvinii" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="colvinii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma colvinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its large ellipsoid spores, reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma psammophilum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="psammophilum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma psammophilum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is currently known only from western Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
